answers.body_markdown:
Comparisons in PowerShell have a tendency to yield unexpected results, because PowerShell tries to [adjust the type][1] of the second operand to match the type of the first operand. Thus if your first operand is a string the comparison will be a string comparison, not a numeric comparison.

**Demonstration:**

&lt;pre&gt;
PS C:\&gt; &lt;b&gt;$s = &#39;20&#39;&lt;/b&gt;
PS C:\&gt; &lt;b&gt;$s -gt 10&lt;/b&gt;    &lt;i&gt;# &amp;hArr; &quot;20&quot; -gt &quot;10&quot;&lt;/i&gt;
True
PS C:\&gt; &lt;b&gt;$s -gt 100&lt;/b&gt;   &lt;i&gt;# &amp;hArr; &quot;20&quot; -gt &quot;100&quot;&lt;/i&gt;
True
PS C:\&gt; &lt;b&gt;$s -gt 3&lt;/b&gt;     &lt;i&gt;# &amp;hArr; &quot;20&quot; -gt &quot;3&quot;&lt;/i&gt;
False
&lt;/pre&gt;

To mitigate this cast the first operand to a numeric type:

&lt;pre&gt;
PS C:\&gt; &lt;b&gt;[int]$s -gt 100&lt;/b&gt;
False
PS C:\&gt; &lt;b&gt;[int]$s -gt 3&lt;/b&gt;
True
&lt;/pre&gt;

 [1]: http://blogs.msdn.com/b/powershell/archive/2006/12/24/boolean-values-and-operators.aspx

